  "response": "The development of calculators was a gradual process with contributions from many inventors over time. Here are some key milestones:\n\n1. Mechanical Calculators:\n- Wilhelm Schickard (1623) created the first mechanical calculating machine\n- Blaise Pascal (1642) invented the Pascaline, an early mechanical calculator\n- Gottfried Leibniz (1671) improved on Pascal's design\n\n2. Electronic Calculators:\n- The first electronic calculators were developed in the 1960s\n- Texas Instruments and Hewlett-Packard were pioneers in developing electronic calculators\n- Jack Kilby (from Texas Instruments) is credited with creating the integrated circuit that made electronic calculators possible\n- In 1967, Texas Instruments introduced the first handheld electronic calculator\n\n3. Pocket Calculators:\n- In 1972, Hewlett-Packard released the HP-35, the first scientific pocket calculator\n\nSo while no single person can be credited as the sole \"inventor\" of the calculator, multiple inventors contributed to its development over centuries, with significant advancements made in the mid-20th century.",
